How String is Immutable (The "A = A + 'R'" Paradox)
  When you perform A = A + "R", you aren't actually changing the original "Baskar" object. 
  Instead, you are creating a brand-new object in memory and moving the label "A" to point at it.
  Here is what happens step-by-step in the String Constant Pool:
     String A = "Baskar"; → Java creates an object "Baskar" in the pool. A points to it.
     A + "R" → Java looks at "Baskar", sees you want to add "R", and creates a completely new string object: "BaskarR".
     A = ... → The variable A stops pointing at "Baskar" and now points to "BaskarR".
   The original object "Baskar" stays exactly the same in memory until it is garbage collected.
   Immutability means the data inside the object cannot change; it doesn't mean the variable cannot point to something else.
    
  Why String is Immutable?
      Security (used in URL, DB, file paths)
      Thread-safe
      Caching (String Pool)
      Performance

Why we can't extend the String class
  In Java, the String class is declared as final. This means you cannot do public class MyString extends String. 
  There are three main reasons for this:
  A. Security
      Strings are used everywhere in sensitive areas: Database URLs, usernames, passwords, and file paths. 
      If String were not final, someone could create a "MutableString" subclass.
        The Threat: You might pass a "String" to a method that checks a file's permissions. 
        While the method is checking, a malicious subclass could change the underlying text from /safe/directory to /etc/passwords. 
        By making it final, Java ensures that a String's value remains constant and trustworthy.
  
  B. The String Constant Pool
     As mentioned above, Java saves memory by sharing identical strings in a pool. 
     If you could extend String and change its behavior (making it mutable), it would corrupt the pool. 
     If two variables point to "Baskar" and one person changes it to "BaskarR", the other person's variable would unexpectedly change too.
  
  C. Performance (Hash-code Caching)
      Because Strings cannot change, their hashCode() is calculated once and cached. 
      This makes them incredibly fast when used as keys in a HashMap.
      If you could extend and modify the string, the hash-code would have to be recalculated constantly, destroying performance.
 
