Exception and Error:
  Exception Handling: 
    Exception handling is a mechanism to handle runtime errors so the program does not crash and continues execution.
         int a = 10;
         int b = 0;
         int result = a / b;  // ❌ ArithmeticException  -> Program crashes
     With Exception Handling:
        try {
            int result = a / b;
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero");
        } ->Program continues safely

  Exception Hierarchy:
        Throwable
         ├── Error
         └── Exception
               ├── Checked Exception
               └── Runtime Exception (Unchecked)

   Error:
     Errors are serious problems caused by JVM/system that your application should NOT try to handle.
     When do Errors happen?
         When something goes wrong at JVM / system level

     Common Scenarios:
         1. ❌ Memory Full
         List<int[]> list = new ArrayList<>();
         while (true) {
             list.add(new int[1000000]);
         } 💥 OutOfMemoryError
         
         2. ❌ Infinite Recursion
             void recurse() {
                 recurse();
             } 💥 StackOverflowError
         
         3. ❌ JVM Internal Failure -> Rare, but possible
         
     Types of Errors:
          OutOfMemoryError
          StackOverflowError
          VirtualMachineError
          AssertionError
     Key Points:
         ❌ Not recoverable
         ❌ Not meant to be caught
         ❌ Caused by system/JVM

  Exception:
     Exceptions are problems caused by application logic or user input, and can be handled.
     When do Exceptions happen?
         During program execution (runtime) due to bad logic or unexpected input
     🔹 Common Scenarios
        1. Divide by zero - int x = 10 / 0; -> ArithmeticException
        2. Null reference -String s = null;  s.length();-> NullPointerException
        3. Invalid index - int[] arr = new int[2]; arr[5] = 10; ->ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
        4. File not found - new FileReader("abc.txt"); -> FileNotFoundException (Checked)

  Feature	     Error	             Exception
  Type	        JVM/System issue  	Application issue
  Recoverable	 ❌ No	             ✅ Yes
  Handling     	Avoid	            Must/Can handle
  Example	      OutOfMemoryError	 NullPointerException

Types of Exceptions:
 1. Checked Exceptions (Compile-time) -> Must be handled
      Examples:
          IOException
          SQLException
          FileReader fr = new FileReader("file.txt"); // must handle
 2. Unchecked Exceptions (Runtime) -> Not mandatory to handle
      Examples:
          NullPointerException
          ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
          ArithmeticException

